<br>
 Ok, you're good at juggling numbers. This &quot;proof&quot; isn't enough though, unless you can also prove that your ship can make it happen. How much starting mass, how much finished mass? How much cargo?<br>
<br>
 If your proposed ship has zero or negative cargo it's worthless. If it has zero or negative structural mass to carry the propellant required to make the delta-V you cite, it's impossible. If the mass of the propellant is zero or negative to allow the ship to carry it, it's also impossible, unless you also design the anti-inertia magazines it's stored in, or a system of matter transmission to send them to the ship in time for them to be shot out the back. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 255<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/02 12:25:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: fast enough?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Truth. That's something Germany never figured out... you just can't take on the whole world... unless you just happen to have an...<br>
