<br>
Back-of-the-envelope figures for JohnF:<br>
<br>
1) tmayes' 467,000 meters/sec maximum velocity<br>
2) 10 m/sec/sec acceleration (1 g)<br>
3) F. Dyson's practical maximum delta-V of 30 m/s per pulse<br>
<br>
Implies one atomblast every three seconds<br>
<br>
467,000 / 30 = ~15,500 atom bombs per &quot;burn&quot;<br>
<br>
Outbound:<br>
TMI = 15,500 bombs<br>
MOI = 15,500 bombs<br>
<br>
Homebound:<br>
TEI = 15,500 bombs<br>
EOI = 15,500 bombs<br>
---------------------<br>
~62,000 bombs roundtrip<br>
<br>
===================================<br>
<br>
Bomb mass:<br>
<br>
Yield to weight ratio (KT/KG of bomb)<br>
Middle of the road bomb = 1.5 to 2.5 kt/kg<br>
Excellent design bomb = 3-5 kt/kg<br>
Likely maximum = ~6 kt/kg<br>
<br>
This is only for the bomb itself. The bulk of the mass is for the plastic propellent, which may dwarf the bomb mass.<br>
------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
It is much to late in the evening for me to even attempt to <br>
create a realistic Mars ship mass-ratio out of these numbers. Be my guest. I'll see if I can do some number crunching this weekend.<br>
<br>
