 A single orion pulse unit can deliver enough momentum<br>
to accelerate orion by 1000, or even 10,000  meters per second with just  one pu detonation. This momentum can be absorbed by the pneumonic steel springs behind the pusher plate .<br>
<br>
 The springs are compressed when the pu debris hits the plate. Then this momentum can be released slowly over a period of minutes or hours or days  as the springs slowly expand back to their origional position, that they had before the pu detonated. In this way orion can operate like a <br>
spring driven toy or watch. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/9/02 4:03:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: fast enough?</span><hr size=1> Here is my 1 stage  super Orion design for a solar system <br>
cruiser.This Orion ship was designed by me in 1981.<br>
<br>
The maximium  mass ratio is  5/1 .<br>
The pu magizine has a mass of 80,000,000 kilograms, and is made of steel.<br>
The impulse absorber system has a mass of 10,000,000<br>
kilograms. The payload has a mass of 10,000,000<br>
kilograms also. The ship diameter is 3300 meters <br>
and the ships height is about 1100 meters.<br>
The orion has a cylindrical shape.<br>
The total orion Mass is 500,000,000 kilograms<br>
The pulse units have a mass of 400,000,000 kilograms.<br>
There are 80,000 (5,000)  kilogram 10 megaton fusion pulse units<br>
<br>
Each pulse unit has a mass of 5,000 kilograms, and a yield<br>
of 10 megatons. The pulse unit  debris velocity is 30,000,000 meters per second which is 30,000 kilometers per second.<br>
 The massive steel pusher plate is backed by very massive steel pneumonic springs.It has a diameter of about 3300 meters.<br>
<br>
 The 10 megaton yield is created by the nuclear fusion<br>
of 500 kilograms of lithium 6 deuteride contained inside of a 500 kilogram lead bottle . The pulse units are wrapped with an outer  casing of berylium metal whose atomic weight is 9.<br>
<br>
This is the propellant used by the pulse units. The inner casing of the pulse units is made of lead metal to facilitate<br>
the process of radiation implosion of the fusion fuel plus block<br>
the nuclear radiation from escaping outside of the device before detonation occurrs.<br>
<br>
 The 10 megaton fireball produced by the pu detonation also<br>
 has a diameter of 3300 meters. Thus we can achieve a collimation factor of 50% .This means the effective specific impulse is 1,500,000 seconds (.05 C ) for this orion.<br>
<br>
The mass of the pulse unit is 5,000 kilograms, which is <br>
thrown outward at 30,000 kilometers (30,000,000 meters)  per second when the pu explodes. This is 10% of light<br>
 velocity<br>
<br>
With 50% collimation : 2500 kilograms of the pu mass in the form of plasma gas will hit the impulse absorber system.<br>
It will transfer 75,000,000 ,000 kilograms ( 750,000,000,000) newtons  of momentum to the orion, which has a mass of  of 500,000,000 kilograms.<br>
<br>
 This means that each pulse unit will change orions velocity by 150 meters per second. This is 15 gs for one second of initial peak acceleration. The springs behind the pusher plate will absorb this momemtum, and slow the acceleration down to a maximium of 1g for 15 seconds after the detonation of a pu. So 4000 pu detonations will generate at least 600,000<br>
meters per second in deta v.This is 600 kilometers per second, which is   is 360 miles per second which equals 1,350,000 miles per hour.<br>
<br>
 The rocket eqaution for orion nuclear pulse rockets  is delta v = effective ve * ln mass ratio.<br>
<br>
Here ve effective is 15,000,000 meters per second , <br>
and the mass ratio is 5/1. <br>
Ln of 5/1 is 1.6.<br>
So delta v maximium for this orion is <br>
15,000,000 * 1.6 meters per second which is<br>
24,000,000 meters per second which is 8% of light velocity.<br>
8% percent of light velocity is 14,900 miles per second<br>
This is 53,600,000 miles an hour <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujackelpdw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jAcKeLPDW</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/17/02 7:38:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.tampabay.rr.com/jackelpdw/jAcKeLPDW.bmp WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  All this is great and stuff...</span><hr size=1> But how is a human body going to be able to withstand the pressure put on it like that... I mean speeds of 53,000,000 km/hour? I think a human or ship would literally be ripped apart... <p><center>---jAcKeLPDW</center>
